pullRequest.body:
Note that this is more resource intensive, as all `hint` tactics will start running at once.

I've worked out how to thread through cancellation hooks so as soon as one succeeds, any still running are cancelled. (If they are doing kernel computations or IO they might not listen, however!)

---

- [x] depends on: #8635

I've had to make this depend on #8635 to avoid breaking an `assert_not_exists` statement.

I've put the parallelism through some paces on my end, making sure that it e.g. doesn't propagate state between tasks, does in fact start all tasks before cancelling, leaves the outer monad in an appropriate state after `takeUpToFirst` and `asArray`, etc.... It behaved as expected in all cases! :)

These review comments are mostly very small and quick style changes for readability (and therefore maintainability). I tried to get rid of `.2.1` style access in favor of clearer destructuring.

There's one meaningful comment in the test file, which is on how `aesop` produces a warning in one case which isn't reflected in the suggestions.

I did eventually figure out how to reduce all of the `MLList.Meta` code via `MonadControl`, but it preferably [requires a core change](https://leanprover.zulipchat.com/#narrow/stream/270676-lean4/topic/.60StateRefT'.60.20.60MonadControl.60.20instance.3F) because the instance is a bit wonky. We can leave that for another PR! :)

What's the explanation for this change? Does `simp_all only` win a race? Is it deterministic?
(Same question for the other changes below, too.)

yes, `simp_all` is faster. These tests are indeed nondeterministic now, and if that becomes a problem we'll have to remove them (or perhaps set an option to disable parallelism?)

I've compiled this file many times locally and the guard conditions haven't failed so far.
In CI, of course, the non-determinism showed up. I've removed some of the `guard_msg` conditions.

Here for example we used to run `linarith` first, and as it succeeded that was all that was reported.

Now `exact?` succeeds more quickly, and that prevents `linarith` being reported.

Minor, but I think we may as well flip the tuple order in `fix?'`; that way
1. the result intuitively matches the order they appear in the resulting `MLList` (`(b, a)` -> `.cons b (fix?' f a)`)
2. we don't need to swap the result in `ofTaskList`
```suggestion
partial def fix?' [Monad m] (f : α → m (Option (β × α))) (init : α) : MLList m β :=
  squash fun _ => do
    match ← f init with
    | none => pure .nil
    | some (b, a) => pure (.cons b (fix?' f a))

/--
Give a list of tasks, return the monadic lazy list which
returns the values as they become available.
-/
def ofTaskList (tasks : List (Task α)) : MLList BaseIO α :=
  fix?' (init := tasks) fun t => do
    if h : 0 < t.length then
      some <$> IO.waitAny' t h
```

Would it be useful to indicate that this came from a task? Or do we want to simply propagate it upwards? Just wanted to bring up the notion.
```suggestion
  | .error e => throwError m!"Task failed:\n{e}")
```

```suggestion
  match results.find? fun (_, mvars, _) => mvars.isEmpty with
```

```suggestion
  return results.qsort fun (_, mvars₁, _) (_, mvars₂, _) => mvars₁.length < mvars₂.length
```

I noticed that `aesop`, when clicked, produces a warning "aesop: failed to prove the goal after exhaustive search." Maybe this is out of scope of this PR, but I wanted to bring it up; perhaps either
1. we should evaluate tactics with warnings as failures (iirc there's a combinator for this?)
2. we should check if warnings were generated in `msgs`, and style the suggestion via `SuggestionStyle.warning` if so

But I'm not sure what the best choice is here.
I think the second option is good, but let's not do it here. Leo is keen to move this all to Std asap, so I'd prefer to not put extra hurdles in front of the move (after the move is great!).
